  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1853794438" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1853794438" />
    <a title="Tina Haigler" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30268418-tina-haigler"><img alt="Tina Haigler" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1396641790p2/30268418.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1853794438?book_show_action=true">May 29, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tina Haigler" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tina Haigler" href="/user/show/30268418-tina-haigler">Tina Haigler</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover " href="/book/show/29430012-a-gentleman-in-moscow">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30268418-tina-haigler?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1853794438" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5296565343864000191"><b>&quot;At half past six on the twenty-first of June 1922, when Count Alexander Ilyich Rostov was escorted through the gates of the Kremlin onto Red Square, it was glorious and cool.&quot;</b><br/><br/>If I could give this more stars, I would. I loved every second of this book. There are only two books in my adult life that have moved me beyond what I thought possible, from beginning to end: A Man Called Ove and A Gentleman in Moscow. I can not possibly express the level of emotions I felt while reading this. The words j</span>
  <span id="freeText5296565343864000191" style="display:none"><b>"At half past six on the twenty-first of June 1922, when Count Alexander Ilyich Rostov was escorted through the gates of the Kremlin onto Red Square, it was glorious and cool."</b><br /><br />If I could give this more stars, I would. I loved every second of this book. There are only two books in my adult life that have moved me beyond what I thought possible, from beginning to end: A Man Called Ove and A Gentleman in Moscow. I can not possibly express the level of emotions I felt while reading this. The words just don't exist.<br /><br />Instead, I will simply tell you that I loved every word. I honestly don't think this author used any of the same adjectives or adverbs twice. I have never seen such a mastery of the English language in my life. I learned so much reading this - vocabulary, Russian history, etiquette, even about wine and food. I spent as much of my time looking things up, as I did reading.<br /><br />I also genuinely enjoyed the characters. Most of them were good people, but there were a few whom I disliked. Good or bad, all of them were so rich and fully fleshed out that they all felt real to me. I truly felt their emotions the whole time. You know those quizzes and polls where they ask if you could meet any fictional character in real life, who would it be? I would choose Count Rostov.<br /><br />I think that's all for now. I honestly can't think of anything else. Essentially I could keep typing love over and over like a maniac, but I think you get the point. So I'll end by saying this - if you haven't read this book, go straight to your nearest library or book store. Don't wait, just go. You can thank me later. Honestly, everyone needs this book in their life. I plan on rereading it for the rest of mine.<br /><br /><b>"And there in the corner, at a table for two, her hair tinged with gray, the willowy woman waited."</b><br /><br />*I also listened to the audiobook version. The narrator does a ridiculously fantastic job, and all the characters have distinct voices. I highly recommend it as well.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5296565343864000191" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

